I often think that the Millennium Generation may be the last generation that can truly appreciate art and connect with artists. They have no such pressure, and do not need to view everything through the critical, colored glasses.
We grew up in the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of pop culture, but today, that collective consciousness has disappeared.
Back then, we didn’t need to worry about the source of the content, and we could directly immerse ourselves in it, because in that era, tracing the origin was not an easy thing.
We reverence these artists as deities, and there's no reason to question this reverence. As a result, a kind of "quasi-social relationship" has been established between us and them, and it has become an indispensable part of our lives.
This also explains why we're so nostalgic.
During the time when this office drama was still on air, my friends and I would gather together every Thursday, eating pizza while watching the drama.
It's a vastly different experience from watching a show on streaming services now, where platforms typically drop 12 episodes at once, with viewers able to watch at their own pace, posting about plot twists on social media while issuing "spoiler warnings", or simply discussing in designated groups.
In the subconscious, we all yearn to relive that collective sense of belonging that connects everyone.
It is precisely because of the nostalgia complex that we repeatedly re-watch TV dramas like "The Office" or movies like "The King of Comedy," and the classic dialogue in these works, like memes, are widely spread online.
We will quote these classic lines from the works and believe that most people will understand the implication.
Even if something goes viral online, we cannot assume that everyone has seen it.
Nowadays, the information explosion is overwhelming, and there are simply too many things we need to pay attention to, making it impossible to streamline... Do we still have a chance to escape this state of information overload?
We keep finding new media and new artists, but instead, we either find those who are riddled with misconduct and perpetrators of sexual abuse, or those who spout prejudice and dogmatic views, and so on, tiresomely.
We are torn between nostalgia and the recognition that the creators of our beloved art may have had serious moral flaws, leaving us feeling at a loss.
We will establish a "quasi-social relationship" with artists in a more careful and delicate manner.
We have gradually come to realize that it is difficult to ensure that one will not hurt or exploit others in order to acquire wealth and power.
Due to the collective consciousness of the media no longer existing, we have formed a class consciousness, which helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, some people are still stubbornly ignorant to this day, insisting on putting others on a pedestal, only to be shocked when their idols collapse.
We are in an era of transformation, and I am eager to know which direction we are heading.
